sm and anti-colonialism, 'otherness', sexuality, sexual rights, the harem and the veil, space and writing, and aboriginal and indigenous women's issues. Not only does this anthology address the lack of attention to gender and feminism in early studies of colonial discourse, it also provides resources for readers to trace the developments in feminism as it responds to postcolonial critiques of First World feminism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aFeminismxHistory. 0aFeminist theoryxHistory. 0aPostcolonialism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aAng, len, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlunt, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoone, Joseph A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrah, Avtar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Sarah Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarby, Hazel V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChow, Rey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Natalie Zemon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl Guind, Fadwa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaggis, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHooks, Bell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Jane M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKandiyoti, Deniz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Reina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/